body:
Thanks for the patch. Couple of general comments about the metrics changes:
1. This works fine when we remove a Sensor using the Metrics reference. However, it is possible to use Sensors this way:

Sensor s;
void create() {
s = metrics.sensor(xx); 
}

void process {
  s.record()
}

Even if the metric is deleted, it is possible to continually record() changes and the writer thread will never know. Should s.record() throw an Exception? 
1. I think it is possible to deadlock if we call Metrics.removeSensor() and Sensor.add(MetricName..) at the same time.

Alternative implementation makes sure that `buffer` size
does not grow over `commitInterval`, but it's more verbose:

```
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put("bootstrap.servers", "localhost:9092");
        props.put("group.id", "test");
        props.put("enable.auto.commit", "false");
        props.put("auto.commit.interval.ms", "1000");
        props.put("session.timeout.ms", "30000");
        props.put("key.deserializer", "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer");
        props.put("value.deserializer", "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer");
        KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
        consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList("foo", "bar"));
        int commitInterval = 200;
        List<ConsumerRecord<String, String>> buffer = new ArrayList<>();
        Map<TopicPartition, Long> consumedOffsets = new HashMap<>();
        while (true) {
            ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(100);
            for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                buffer.add(record);
                consumedOffsets.put(new TopicPartition(record.topic(), record.partition()), record.offset());
                if (buffer.size() >= commitInterval) {
                    insertIntoDb(buffer);
                    consumer.commitSync(consumedOffsets);
                    buffer.clear();
                    consumedOffsets.clear();
                }
            }
        }
```

Here we commit every 200 records as in original example, but we have to maintain 
the consumed offsets manually, so we don't commit records that haven't been inserted
into the database yet.
